\subsection{Bilingual Language Profile}
\label{ssec:BLP}
One instrument used in this study was the Bilingual Language Profile (BLP), which is a survey based assessment tool for determining language dominance \parencite{Birdsong2012-wd}. Through its 19 questions, it assesses language history, use, proficiency and attitudes of participants in less than 10 minutes. It is available in many languages, but given that all participants recruited for in-person experiments for this dissertation were bilinguals of only Spanish and English, these were the two language pairings used. This tool allowed for the collection of information about participants demographics---name, age, sex, place of residence and educational background---which took place at experiment setup in the current study. It also allowed for participants to indicate their language history, use, proficiency and attitudes and was the last task completed during the current study. Since the BLP survey was completed after all experimental trials, the participants were able to choose whether they received Spanish or English instructions and questions for the survey. The language display of the BLP was done programmatically based off the participant's response to the preferred language question at the beginning of the experiment setup. The placement of the BLP as the final task was done intentionally because it generated the most questions for participants in how to respond during an unofficial pilot study of the experiment. In addition, it avoided potentially activating one language over another prior to experimental tasks where response times were being recorded for analysis. Activating one language over another could have affected the response times being collected for Spanish items, which were a critical part of the experimental design.

The BLP assessment tool has been used in numerous language studies with a focus on bilingualism and is available for free under the creative commons license. The BLP is available in a paper-based format and electronically through the use of Google Forms. However, in an effort to make the time in the lab and the feel of the experiment as seamless as possible, the participants in this dissertation took the BLP within the PsychoPy platform as well. \ttodo[inline]{This only works if PyschoPy is explained before this point. Otherwise it needs to be reworded.} No modifications were made to BLP questions or their ordering, but they were formatted in a .csv file that PsychoPy could read. During the experiment, the language that the question was interested in changed color to highlight the difference for participants---English was written in purple, Spanish in blue and other languages in red. \ttodo[inline]{This description is unclear to readers who are not familiar with BLP. Explain what the survey looked like in plain English} In addition to it being the last item of the experiment, it was also untimed allowing for the participant to ask clarification questions about the survey as it was taking place in their preferred language choice without compromising the integrity of the data of the experiments focused on the processing of Spanish. 

