\subsection{English Vocabulary Size}
\label{ssec:LexTALE}
In order to better understand the English language proficiency of participants, the Lexical Test for Advanced Learners of English (LexTALE) was used. \ttodo[inline]{citation} The LexTALE contains 60 vocabulary items presented as an untimed visual lexical decision task plus three additional practice items that always appeared as the first three items. The LexTALE task is used to correlate vocabulary knowledge and language proficiency in English \parencite{Lemhofer2012-hz}. According to the findings of Lemhöfer \& Broersma \parencite*{Lemhofer2012-hz}, self-ratings such as writing, reading, listening and speaking proficiency, while significant in some cases, did not have the same predicative power as the LexTALE for translation accuracy and overall proficiency. For example, the LexTALE vocabulary test was able to distinguish between lower intermediate (up to 59 percent), upper intermediate (60–80 percent) and advanced (above 80 percent) levels of proficiency based on average percent correct responses. In terms of word recognition experiments, the LexTALE remained a significant predictor of success while self-ratings was not \parencite{Lemhofer2012-hz}. The LexTALE task is publicly available online at www.lextale.com and has been designed to run in PRAAT, Matlab and Presentation. For data collection purposes in this disseration project, participants completed both the LexTALE using PsychoPy to create the feel of a single, connected experimental session.

Similar to the BLP, participants in the NS and LS groups that completed experiments in-person took the LexTALE. \ttodo[inline]{This is unclear and hard to read.} The MS group did not participate in the LexTALE task for fear that they may become discouraged at the fact they must guess whether a word is real or not in a language for which they had no prior knowledge when the experiment was advertised as a Spanish language study.\ttodo[inline]{English ability was not concern here.} As a result, the LS group who completed the experiment in an online setting did not complete this task in an effort to keep the experimental environment as similar as possible to their comparison MS group, monolingual Spanish speakers.\ttodo[inline]{Targeting native English speakers so no need to test their English ability.} Also like the BLP task, the LexTALE task also followed all tasks where Spanish and reaction times in relation to processing Spanish were recorded. This allowed the allowed the instructions for the task to be presented to participants in English or Spanish based off of their response to \emph{preferred language} in the experiment startup dialog box.

For the participants completing the LexTALE, they were instructed that they were going to see strings of letters appear on the screen and that they were to respond \emph{yes} if they thought the letters were actually a real word in English and to respond \emph{no} if they believed the word to not exist in English. The instructions also clearly indicated that the task was untimed and that they could take as much time as they needed to respond. The participant pressed a button on the provided button box to begin the task and the first word appeared in the center of the screen along with \emph{sí} below the word and to the left of center screen while \emph{no} appeared below the word and to the right of center screen. PyschoPy kept the screen constant until the participant entered the response through the button box. When PyschoPy registered a response, it displayed the next word in the task until the participant had responded to all 60 items and displayed the instructions for the next section. All participants saw the 60 items in the same order.

The scoring of the LexTALE task is reported as a percentage of correct responses. The first step was to remove the first three items as they were practice items and should not count towards the participant's score. This left the 60 experimental items remaining, where 40 of them were real English word and 20 were nonwords. Equation \ref{eqn:LexTALE_eq} was used in accordance with the documentation provided by the LexTALE creators. This equation also corrected for the proportion inequality of words versus nonwords used in the task. A full list of items and materials used in this project can be found in Appendix \ref{Appendix_LexTALE}.

\begin{equation}
Score_{LexTALE} = \frac{(\frac{n_{Word}}{40}*100) + (\frac{n_{Nonword}}{20}*100)}{2} 
\label{eqn:LexTALE_eq}
\end{equation}
\begin{align*}
\intertext{where:}
Score_{LexTALE} & = \text{reported as percentage correct}\\[-2ex]
n_{Word} & = \text{number of correct responses to real words}\\[-2ex]
n_{Nonword} & = \text{number of correct responses to nonwords}\\[-2ex]
\end{align*}
