All participants reported in this dissertation project regardless of whether they were recruited for in-person or online data collection completed the LexTALE-Esp. Every participant completed the LexTALE-Esp as the initial task of the experiment. This was done intentionally to serve as a buffer of language mode activation, which could have affected reaction times in the Spanish processing tasks. This was necessary since many of the LS group participants were very likely to speak in English with the researcher througout the consent obtaining process. As with the LexTALE task, participants were instructed that they were going to see strings of letters appear on the screen and that they were to respond \emph{sí} if they thought the letters represented a real Spanish word and to respond \emph{no} if they believed the word did not exist in Spanish. The instructions clearly indicated that they could take as much time as they needed to respond as the task was untimed. Participants pressed a button on the provided button box to begin the task which brough up the initial trial screen. The first word appeared in the center of the screen along with available responses also displaying below the word and off of center screen. The \emph{sí} response appeared to the left of center screen while \emph{no} response appeared to the right of center screen. PyschoPy waited until it registered a response through the button box before it displayed the next word in the task. This cycle repeated until the participant had responded to all 90 items and the instructions for the next section were displayed on the screen. No randomization of item presentation order was utilized as in the LexTALE task. \ttodo{ This is a feature of LexTALE. Say that so it is clear as to why I made this choice and be clear that it was not a personal decision that was unfounded.}

The scoring of the LexTALE-Esp task is only documented in Izura, Cuetos and Brysbaert \parencite*{Izura2014-yw}. While it differs from the LexTALE calculation, equation \ref{eqn:LexTALE-Esp_eq} used in the LexTALE-Esp remains quite simple, but does report the score as a percentage of correct responses. Since, the current project added three practice trials, the first step was to remove them because they should not count towards the participant's score. This left the 60 real Spanish words and 30 Spanish nonwords which were used in the computation of each participant's Spanish vocabulary score.

\begin{equation}
Score_{LexTALE-Esp} = n_{Word} - 2 * n_{Nonword}
\label{eqn:LexTALE-Esp_eq}
\end{equation}
\begin{align*}
\intertext{where:}
n_{Word} & = \text{number of yes responses to real words}\\[-2ex]
n_{Nonword} & = \text{number of yes responses to nonwords}\\[-2ex]
\end{align*}

In case other researcher preferred the percentage score, Izura, Cuetos and Brysbaert \parencite*{Izura2014-yw} provided equation \ref{eqn:LexTALE-ESP-percent_eq} as a footnote in the documentation. However, all LexTALE-Esp scores reported in the current project were calculated using equation \ref{eqn:LexTALE-Esp_eq}. The complete list of materials used for the LexTALE-Esp are included in Appendix \ref{Appendix_LexTALE-Esp}.

\begin{equation}
Score_{LexTALE-Esp} = \frac{n_{Word}}{60} - \frac{n_{Nonword}}{30}
\label{eqn:LexTALE-ESP-percent_eq}
\end{equation}
\begin{align*}
\intertext{where:}
Score_{LexTALE-Esp} & = \text{reported as percentage correct}\\[-2ex]
n_{Word} & = \text{number of yes responses to real words}\\[-2ex]
n_{Nonword} & = \text{number of yes responses to nonwords}\\[-2ex]
\end{align*}
